WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:02.510
&gt;&gt; From the Library of Congress
in Washington, DC.

00:00:02.510 --> 00:00:15.060
[ Silence ]

00:00:15.060 --> 00:00:16.530 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much for joining us.

00:00:16.530 --> 00:00:23.200 position:69%
This is the first even online conference for
the Library of Congress and for educators.

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:27.820
We have a fabulous program
lined up for you right now.

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:33.010 position:61%
During this session, you'll learn how
to use free online assessments designed

00:00:33.010 --> 00:00:36.780
by the Stanford History Education
Group that incorporate documents

00:00:36.780 --> 00:00:39.460 position:63%
from the Library of Congress's archives.

00:00:39.460 --> 00:00:44.440 position:63%
Participants will examine assessments,
rubrics, and sample students' responses.

00:00:44.440 --> 00:00:47.760
Leading us through this session
is Joel Breakstone.

00:00:47.760 --> 00:00:52.960 position:64%
Joel co-directs the Teaching With Primary
Sources Program at Stanford University.

00:00:52.960 --> 00:00:56.720
And directs the Stanford
History Education Group.

00:00:56.720 --> 00:01:00.500
Along with Mark Smith and Sam
Wineberg, he led the development

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:04.840 position:59%
of Stanford History Education Group's
assessment website, Beyond the Bubble.

00:01:04.840 --> 00:01:08.510
He received his PhD from Stanford
Graduate School of Education.

00:01:08.510 --> 00:01:13.650 position:59%
And before coming to Stanford, he
taught high school history in Vermont.

00:01:13.650 --> 00:01:16.060 position:64%
So I'm going to turn things over to Joel.

00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:18.340
&gt;&gt; Thanks so much, Kathy.

00:01:18.340 --> 00:01:20.330 position:58%
I really appreciate the introduction.

00:01:20.330 --> 00:01:23.160
I'm really pleased to be
with all of you this evening.

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:25.730
And I want to also just reiterate
my thanks to the Library

00:01:25.730 --> 00:01:28.650 position:67%
of Congress for organizing this conference.

00:01:28.650 --> 00:01:31.530
It's a really excellent opportunity
for teachers,

00:01:31.530 --> 00:01:34.690
and we're really excited to
be able to participate in it.

00:01:34.690 --> 00:01:38.190 position:61%
My colleague, Sam Wineberg, just
finished up a session that perhaps some

00:01:38.190 --> 00:01:41.610 position:72%
of you had a chance to hear him speak as well.

00:01:41.610 --> 00:01:48.190 position:64%
Over the course of the next 40 minutes
or so, I hope to give you an introduction

00:01:48.190 --> 00:01:54.830 position:72%
to the materials that we've created and have
posted online on beyondthebubble.stanford.edu.

00:01:54.830 --> 00:01:58.990 position:75%
And to not only provide introduction to the
materials, but also to provide a bit of a window

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:03.960 position:66%
into the process by which we designed
them and what we hope they are useful for.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:09.980 position:73%
But before I get to that, I want to just say a
little bit about how I ended up doing this work

00:02:09.980 --> 00:02:12.910
and being at the Stanford
History Education Group.

00:02:12.910 --> 00:02:17.190 position:61%
I was a -- as Kathy mentioned -- a
high school history teacher in Vermont.

00:02:17.190 --> 00:02:22.280
But I came to that position after
being a history major in college.

00:02:22.280 --> 00:02:25.670
And I graduated from college
and I didn't have a job.

00:02:25.670 --> 00:02:31.450 position:69%
And I ended up getting offered a position in
Vermont, even though I had only spent a day

00:02:31.450 --> 00:02:33.370
in Vermont before getting the job.

00:02:33.370 --> 00:02:37.440
I moved there from Boston
-- I had grown up in Boston.

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:40.970 position:61%
And I took over for a gentleman who had
been teaching for a number of years.

00:02:40.970 --> 00:02:48.330 position:64%
And the main things that I inherited were
a classroom set of the American Pageant.

00:02:48.330 --> 00:02:55.010 position:67%
And I knew that although the textbook would
be a great starting place for my students,

00:02:55.010 --> 00:02:59.640 position:64%
it wasn't the only thing that I wanted my
students to read in their history class.

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:02.380 position:70%
And so I wanted them to read primary sources.

00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:05.430 position:61%
That is what I read as a history major.

00:03:05.430 --> 00:03:07.760 position:58%
And so I gave my students a document.

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:11.460 position:66%
One of the first ones I gave them was this
great speech by William Lloyd Garrison

00:03:11.460 --> 00:03:20.390 position:72%
in which he describes the hypocrisy of
celebrating the fourth of July in independence

00:03:20.390 --> 00:03:25.950 position:63%
when there are thousands and thousands
of people enslaved in the United States.

00:03:25.950 --> 00:03:32.230 position:64%
And I found quickly that giving a
student a document that is 850 words long

00:03:32.230 --> 00:03:36.810
and in 12-point font at 7:37
in the morning is a bad idea.

00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:41.070 position:58%
And it was that terrible feeling that
I had too often as a young teacher

00:03:41.070 --> 00:03:45.040 position:67%
where the lesson's going poorly and you're
trying to figure out how you can salvage it

00:03:45.040 --> 00:03:49.150 position:75%
so that it goes a little better when you have to
teach it three more times the rest of the day.

00:03:49.150 --> 00:03:52.740 position:64%
And so I figured out some things over the
course of my time teaching in Vermont.

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:56.400 position:58%
But I also had a lot of questions
about how I could do the work better.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:58.740
And how you could provide
more materials for teachers.

00:03:58.740 --> 00:04:03.530 position:66%
Because it's simply unreasonable to expect
that each teacher is going to be able

00:04:03.530 --> 00:04:06.560 position:58%
to create a variety of document-based
materials on their own.

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:10.430 position:69%
It's an incredibly time-consuming process to
track down materials and to build lessons.

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:13.760 position:66%
Certainly you can do some, but it's really
difficult to create an entire curriculum.

00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:21.140 position:69%
And so that's what led me ultimately to pack
up my life's belongings into a Penske truck

00:04:21.140 --> 00:04:29.250 position:69%
and drive across I-80 to California, where I
began a doctoral program at Stanford working

00:04:29.250 --> 00:04:32.270 position:61%
with folks who had similar interests at
the Stanford History Education Group.

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:36.290
Around, how do you create
materials that are available

00:04:36.290 --> 00:04:38.480 position:63%
for teachers to use with their students?

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:42.670 position:59%
And make them in an accessible fashion
so that you don't have the looks

00:04:42.670 --> 00:04:45.580
that my students gave me
that first morning at 7:37

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:47.430 position:70%
where they simply had no interest in reading.

00:04:47.430 --> 00:04:50.920
And in many cases the materials
were simply inaccessible for them.

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:55.930
And when I arrived at Stanford,
we had just released the Reading

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:59.130
Like a Historian curriculum online.

00:04:59.130 --> 00:05:03.470
And we had a lot of interest in it.

00:05:03.470 --> 00:05:05.550
There was a lot of excitement
about the materials.

00:05:05.550 --> 00:05:12.180
But there was also simultaneously
a lot of talk about assessment.

00:05:12.180 --> 00:05:15.500
And it came from the highest
levels of government.

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:20.820 position:59%
Barack Obama, in March of 2009 said,
"I'm calling on our nation's governors

00:05:20.820 --> 00:05:23.660
and state education chiefs to
develop standards and assessments

00:05:23.660 --> 00:05:26.910 position:63%
that don't simply measure whether
students can fill in a bubble on a test,

00:05:26.910 --> 00:05:31.720 position:69%
but whether they possess 21st Century skills
like problem solving and critical thinking."

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:32.420
And we agreed.

00:05:32.420 --> 00:05:34.070
We said, yes, absolutely.

00:05:34.070 --> 00:05:37.120 position:75%
We would love to see those types of assessments.

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:39.710
But where are they?

00:05:39.710 --> 00:05:42.600
That's an excellent goal,
but if you're a teacher,

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:45.060 position:66%
where do you get those types of materials?

00:05:45.060 --> 00:05:48.890
And simultaneously we were
releasing, as I mentioned,

00:05:48.890 --> 00:05:50.450 position:63%
the Reading Like a Historian curriculum.

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:53.480
This is our old website.

00:05:53.480 --> 00:05:59.500
And when we first released the
curriculum, we got a lot of emails

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:01.130 position:66%
from folks who began to use the materials.

00:06:01.130 --> 00:06:05.360 position:56%
And the most common query was, where
are the World History materials?

00:06:05.360 --> 00:06:07.270
Which was a fair critique.

00:06:07.270 --> 00:06:11.020
We've since adjusted and have begun
to make World History materials.

00:06:11.020 --> 00:06:13.750
But the second most common
response that we heard

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:15.690 position:67%
from people was, where are the assessments?

00:06:15.690 --> 00:06:18.750
If you guys are going to make
all these materials based

00:06:18.750 --> 00:06:24.660 position:70%
around teaching historical inquiry and having
students engage in disciplinary reading

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:27.580
and thinking, how do I know whether
or not my students can do it?

00:06:27.580 --> 00:06:30.890
How do I know whether or not they
can consider source information?

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:33.250
Where did the document come from?

00:06:33.250 --> 00:06:35.750 position:70%
What was the context in which it was created?

00:06:35.750 --> 00:06:41.600 position:66%
How does the context in which it was
created shape the content of the document?

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:44.820 position:73%
These historical things need scales of
sourcing, contextualization, and corroboration.

00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:46.590
Which our curriculum was based on.

00:06:46.590 --> 00:06:51.100 position:56%
And then at the same time the
Common Core standards were released.

00:06:51.100 --> 00:06:54.860 position:67%
And they called for students to do things
like analyze primary and secondary sources.

00:06:54.860 --> 00:06:56.260
Consider authors' perspectives.

00:06:56.260 --> 00:06:57.620
Corroborate sources.

00:06:57.620 --> 00:07:00.120 position:64%
And develop written historical arguments.

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:04.070
And we said, you know, these
are some interesting skills.

00:07:04.070 --> 00:07:07.420 position:59%
But how are we going to assess whether
or not our students can do that?

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:12.550 position:70%
These various fairly complex ways of thinking
and reading, where are the assessments

00:07:12.550 --> 00:07:17.190 position:63%
that would help students to engage in --
to give teachers feedback about whether

00:07:17.190 --> 00:07:21.810
or not their students can engage in
these ways of thinking and reading.

00:07:21.810 --> 00:07:24.600 position:56%
And so we continue to ask the
question, where are the assessments?

00:07:24.600 --> 00:07:27.510
But we didn't have a good
answer for where to find them.

00:07:27.510 --> 00:07:32.450
And when you look around, you
can find an enormous number

00:07:32.450 --> 00:07:34.760 position:64%
of materials that talk about assessments.

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:37.170 position:75%
And particularly issues of formative assessment.

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:38.660
How do you create short tasks?

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:44.970
If you go on Amazon you can find
hundreds and hundreds of resources

00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:46.960 position:69%
that you can buy about formative assessment.

00:07:46.960 --> 00:07:54.300 position:72%
But there are not many for history teachers,
for guidance for how do you create short tasks

00:07:54.300 --> 00:07:59.660 position:75%
that give us quick feedback that we can use to
quite literally form our next steps in teaching.

00:07:59.660 --> 00:08:01.130
There wasn't much guidance.

00:08:01.130 --> 00:08:05.680 position:66%
And moreover, there weren't many resources
in the world of formative assessment.

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:09.090
So we weren't sure what these types
of assessments could look like.

00:08:09.090 --> 00:08:13.330 position:56%
But we knew where we could find the
materials to make those assessments.

00:08:13.330 --> 00:08:17.490 position:69%
We had just joined the Library of Congress's
Teaching With Primary Sources Consortium.

00:08:17.490 --> 00:08:21.380 position:61%
And as a result, we suddenly had
access to the world's greatest library.

00:08:21.380 --> 00:08:24.140
And all the resources that
the Library's archives offer.

00:08:24.140 --> 00:08:27.830
And so we knew we wanted to
construct some short tasks

00:08:27.830 --> 00:08:32.830 position:73%
that would provide teachers meaningful feedback
about these ways of historical reading.

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:35.790
But we still weren't sure
exactly what form they would take.

00:08:35.790 --> 00:08:38.730
And so we wanted to be clear
first about what are the resources

00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:42.190
that are immediately available
to history teachers?

00:08:42.190 --> 00:08:46.210
And we see them as existing
on a continuum of complexity.

00:08:46.210 --> 00:08:49.160
At one end of this spectrum
are multiple choice questions,

00:08:49.160 --> 00:08:53.110 position:67%
which are quite familiar to us as teachers.

00:08:53.110 --> 00:08:56.050 position:66%
But also as citizens of the United States.

00:08:56.050 --> 00:08:59.190 position:61%
The United States likes multiple
choice questions more than most places.

00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:03.620 position:58%
In the U.K. They call multiple
choice questions "the American form."

00:09:03.620 --> 00:09:08.180 position:67%
So not everywhere has the same
fascination with multiple choice questions.

00:09:08.180 --> 00:09:12.610 position:64%
And so before we -- we knew that
multiple choice questions were available,

00:09:12.610 --> 00:09:14.650 position:66%
but we wanted to also be very clear about,

00:09:14.650 --> 00:09:19.320 position:58%
what is it that a multiple choice
question requires our students to do?

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:22.270
And it was an important first
step in the design process.

00:09:22.270 --> 00:09:27.840 position:72%
We wanted to be very explicit about the skills
and knowledge that are required for students

00:09:27.840 --> 00:09:31.560 position:58%
to answer a multiple choice question.

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:35.890
And so here's an example drawn
from the California State Test

00:09:35.890 --> 00:09:37.600
for tenth graders, World History.

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:43.560 position:75%
And what I'd like you to do is to take a moment,
read the question, and just think about all

00:09:43.560 --> 00:09:48.030
of the things that a student would
need to know and be able to do

00:09:48.030 --> 00:09:49.850
in order to answer this question.

00:09:49.850 --> 00:09:52.140
So when we give a student
this multiple choice question,

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:53.980 position:61%
what is it that we're really assessing?

00:09:53.980 --> 00:10:01.130 position:75%
And so as you think about that, take a moment
and just type in the chat box some of the skills

00:10:01.130 --> 00:10:04.300
that are required in order
to answer this question.

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:05.960 position:59%
We'll take a minute or two to do that.

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:09.800
And then we'll go on as people
begin to fill in some of the things

00:10:09.800 --> 00:10:12.470
that are required in order
to answer the question.

00:10:12.470 --> 00:10:13.450 position:59%
Think of sort of the most basic thing.

00:10:13.450 --> 00:10:14.560 position:67%
What's the first thing students need to do?

00:10:14.560 --> 00:10:16.510
And then what are some of the
knowledge that they need to know?

00:10:16.510 --> 00:11:14.830
[ Silence ]

00:11:14.830 --> 00:11:18.630
Great. So looking through this
list, you know, I see a lot of --

00:11:18.630 --> 00:11:21.990
there are a lot of things that are
required in order to answer this.

00:11:21.990 --> 00:11:27.520 position:59%
You know, one of the very basic things
is it requires reading comprehension.

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:31.430
Students need to be able to
read and decode the question.

00:11:31.430 --> 00:11:34.190
So somebody wrote down academic
vocabulary, right?

00:11:34.190 --> 00:11:35.440 position:64%
Students need to know what an outcome is.

00:11:35.440 --> 00:11:40.820
And then beyond that, there are
some crucial vocabulary words.

00:11:40.820 --> 00:11:42.690
Like "colonial possessions."

00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:44.190 position:58%
You need to know what a Communist is.

00:11:44.190 --> 00:11:45.560
"Dominant military powers."

00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:46.850
"International superpowers."

00:11:46.850 --> 00:11:51.350 position:67%
So there's some just reading comprehension.

00:11:51.350 --> 00:11:53.900 position:59%
There's also content knowledge, right?

00:11:53.900 --> 00:11:55.910 position:58%
Issues of, how does World War II end?

00:11:55.910 --> 00:12:01.080 position:59%
Right? Students need to know something
in order to answer the question.

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:03.480
And also how to read a test, right?

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:07.570 position:72%
That there's also a basic move of test taking.

00:12:07.570 --> 00:12:12.510
Of eliminating, somebody said,
the wrong answers, right?

00:12:12.510 --> 00:12:14.820
It's that, you know, by the
time a student's in tenth grade,

00:12:14.820 --> 00:12:16.410
they've taken a lot of multiple
choice questions.

00:12:16.410 --> 00:12:19.530
They have a pretty good idea
of how to answer the question.

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:23.150
And so that's about doing
a process of elimination.

00:12:23.150 --> 00:12:27.180 position:72%
And so, you know, when we think about multiple
choice questions, we see them as providing,

00:12:27.180 --> 00:12:31.350
you know, immediate feedback
about students' reasoning.

00:12:31.350 --> 00:12:35.240
But it's not necessarily the
way to measure all of the things

00:12:35.240 --> 00:12:37.880
that we want our students
to know and be able to do.

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:42.630 position:61%
Because it's also measuring some things
that are not particularly historical.

00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:45.520
Like process of elimination.

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:47.990
That's not a move of a historian.

00:12:47.990 --> 00:12:49.380
That's a test-taking move.

00:12:49.380 --> 00:12:55.740 position:73%
Similarly, it doesn't give us a lot of feedback
about students' more complex ways of thinking.

00:12:55.740 --> 00:13:01.040 position:69%
But it's quick and we can do it fairly
efficiently and get some immediate feedback.

00:13:01.040 --> 00:13:03.890
But it may not be the best tool
for measuring all of the things

00:13:03.890 --> 00:13:07.330
that we want our students
to know and be able to do.

00:13:07.330 --> 00:13:12.420 position:63%
At the other end of the spectrum are
DBQ's -- a much more complex, rich task.

00:13:12.420 --> 00:13:18.570 position:69%
One that has gained increasing popularity
as the Advanced Placement program has grown.

00:13:18.570 --> 00:13:21.850
And the State of New York has
used them in their Regents Exams.

00:13:21.850 --> 00:13:27.540
And other groups have provided
materials around DBQ's.

00:13:27.540 --> 00:13:33.220 position:72%
And it's a much richer task, one that requires
students to engage in a variety of skills.

00:13:33.220 --> 00:13:37.440 position:59%
And again, what we did before we moved
on to develop the assessments was,

00:13:37.440 --> 00:13:39.190 position:75%
we wanted to be really clear about, what do some

00:13:39.190 --> 00:13:43.240
of these most common types of
tasks require students to do?

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:48.260 position:56%
So here's an example; this is pulled
from the 2010 AP U.S. History exam.

00:13:48.260 --> 00:13:52.900 position:72%
And it was, "In what ways did ideas and values
held by Puritans influence the political,

00:13:52.900 --> 00:13:58.250 position:73%
economic, and social development of the New
England colonies from 1630 through the 1660's?"

00:13:58.250 --> 00:14:01.090
Students then receive a series
of primary sources.

00:14:01.090 --> 00:14:04.060 position:64%
In this case they received ten documents.

00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:10.350 position:66%
They have then an hour to read through the
documents and formulate an analytic essay,

00:14:10.350 --> 00:14:12.030
and to compose that analytic essay.

00:14:12.030 --> 00:14:17.110 position:63%
And so again, I'd like us to take a
moment and do the same thing that we did

00:14:17.110 --> 00:14:19.850 position:67%
when we were initially surveying the field.

00:14:19.850 --> 00:14:23.480 position:69%
And take a moment and list in the chat box,
what are the things that students have to do

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:26.070 position:72%
from start to finish in order to answer a DBQ?

00:14:26.070 --> 00:14:27.710
So that we can have some clarity
about, what are the skills

00:14:27.710 --> 00:14:29.510
that we're really assessing
with this type of question?

00:14:29.510 --> 00:15:33.520
[ Silence ]

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:36.970
Yes, as this chat box indicates,
it's a lot of things, right?

00:15:36.970 --> 00:15:41.090
I think that's indicative of
the complexity of the task.

00:15:41.090 --> 00:15:49.230 position:67%
Students have to, at a basic level, be able
to have some strong reading comprehension.

00:15:49.230 --> 00:15:51.500 position:58%
They need to first unpack this slide.

00:15:51.500 --> 00:15:54.590
This is not a small thing.

00:15:54.590 --> 00:15:57.450 position:73%
You know, you need to understand this question.

00:15:57.450 --> 00:16:06.010 position:70%
What are the different pieces of the question
that need to be addressed in a response?

00:16:06.010 --> 00:16:09.710 position:75%
And then they need to engage with the documents.

00:16:09.710 --> 00:16:13.620 position:72%
And as people's comments have noted, there are
a variety of things the students have to do.

00:16:13.620 --> 00:16:16.290
They have to skim, they have
to look for context clues.

00:16:16.290 --> 00:16:18.060 position:59%
They need to look for evidence, right?

00:16:18.060 --> 00:16:22.600 position:64%
They need to figure out what is the
argument that they're going to be making,

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:24.800 position:59%
and then seek it out in the documents.

00:16:24.800 --> 00:16:30.530 position:59%
And as several people noted, it's
also about a process of multi-tasking.

00:16:30.530 --> 00:16:35.920 position:61%
You need to be reading at the same time
as thinking how the documents connect

00:16:35.920 --> 00:16:42.070
to the broader argument that
they're seeking to make.

00:16:42.070 --> 00:16:44.030
And then they need to read a map.

00:16:44.030 --> 00:16:45.530 position:63%
They need to understand archaic English.

00:16:45.530 --> 00:16:50.040 position:70%
So they're -- and the ultimately, after
they've done all this reading, and analyzing,

00:16:50.040 --> 00:16:51.450
and organizing, they need to write.

00:16:51.450 --> 00:16:54.690
And write pretty furiously.

00:16:54.690 --> 00:16:59.710 position:72%
In the process, hope their wrist doesn't cramp
up, they can mop some sweat off their brow,

00:16:59.710 --> 00:17:04.320 position:58%
and maybe do a quick proofread
before they're done in about an hour,

00:17:04.320 --> 00:17:09.910 position:73%
within the framework of the traditional AP DBQ.

00:17:09.910 --> 00:17:11.480
It's a rich task.

00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:15.650 position:70%
And it is testing the types of things we want
our students ultimately to be able to do.

00:17:15.650 --> 00:17:21.760 position:64%
To analyze a series of primary documents,
and to write an analytic argument.

00:17:21.760 --> 00:17:24.680
That's what we want our students
to be able to do.

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:29.260
However, it may be a little too
challenging for some students.

00:17:29.260 --> 00:17:32.910
And moreover, its complexity
can make it a little difficult

00:17:32.910 --> 00:17:36.490 position:67%
to discern what a student is doing well at,

00:17:36.490 --> 00:17:38.480
and the things that students
might be struggling with.

00:17:38.480 --> 00:17:41.680 position:59%
If a student doesn't do well on a DBQ,

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:45.970
is it because that they don't
have the reading ability?

00:17:45.970 --> 00:17:50.710 position:70%
Or is it perhaps because they struggle to
orchestrate these various skills all at once?

00:17:50.710 --> 00:17:55.100 position:75%
Or perhaps they don't do well with a timed task?

00:17:55.100 --> 00:18:00.550 position:73%
So as a result, if I'm a teacher and I receive
the DBQ back, it can be a little more difficult

00:18:00.550 --> 00:18:05.740
to figure out, what are my next
steps to help my student do better?

00:18:05.740 --> 00:18:09.170 position:66%
In addition, though, is the issue of time.

00:18:09.170 --> 00:18:13.550
If I'm a teacher and I assign
a DBQ, I then have to do what?

00:18:13.550 --> 00:18:15.740
I have to grade it.

00:18:15.740 --> 00:18:17.170
And that's really time consuming.

00:18:17.170 --> 00:18:24.160 position:73%
And unless you want to spend all of your waking
hours reading student writing, it's not --

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:29.940 position:70%
it's simply unrealistic to expect that we can
use DBQ's for frequent classroom assessment.

00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:33.200
They're a great task, but
they're not ideally suited

00:18:33.200 --> 00:18:36.030 position:73%
for quick feedback about student understanding.

00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:42.150 position:61%
And so as we thought about the spectrum
of assessments that were available

00:18:42.150 --> 00:18:45.900 position:56%
to history/social studies
teachers, we were struck by this gap

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:49.820 position:59%
between the more basic multiple choice
questions and the complex DBQ's.

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:53.050 position:67%
And we hope to be able to provide something

00:18:53.050 --> 00:18:57.540
that could inhabit this middle
ground between the two.

00:18:57.540 --> 00:19:03.640 position:64%
And so in a world of acronyms, we decided
to make our own to fill the middle space,

00:19:03.640 --> 00:19:07.700
what we call "history assessments
of thinkings, or HATs."

00:19:07.700 --> 00:19:12.400 position:63%
And so rather than talk a lot about
what HATs are, I'd like to show you one.

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:16.030 position:56%
To give you an example of one of the
tasks that we created in an effort

00:19:16.030 --> 00:19:19.680 position:66%
to create short document-based assessments

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:22.190
that give us some quick feedback
about specific skills.

00:19:22.190 --> 00:19:25.350 position:58%
This is an assessment that we created

00:19:25.350 --> 00:19:29.450 position:59%
to target very specifically the
historical thinking skill of sourcing.

00:19:29.450 --> 00:19:32.910
That is, can students pay attention
to where a document came from?

00:19:32.910 --> 00:19:33.570
Who made it?

00:19:33.570 --> 00:19:34.770
When? Why?

00:19:34.770 --> 00:19:35.950
And for what purpose?

00:19:35.950 --> 00:19:40.280
And specifically with this task, we
were really interested in whether

00:19:40.280 --> 00:19:43.280
or not students will notice
the date of the document.

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:47.560 position:69%
So this assessment gives students this image
from the Library of Congress's archives.

00:19:47.560 --> 00:19:51.290
The title of the document is,
"First Thanksgiving, 1921."

00:19:51.290 --> 00:19:55.730
The document is from 1932, made
by a guy named J.L.G. Ferris.

00:19:55.730 --> 00:19:59.950 position:64%
And the question is, "This painting helps
historians understand the relationship

00:19:59.950 --> 00:20:03.470
between the Wampanoag and
the Pilgrim settlers in 1621.

00:20:03.470 --> 00:20:05.550
Do you agree or disagree?

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:08.100
Briefly support your answer."

00:20:08.100 --> 00:20:12.530
What I'd like you to do is take a
minute or two and just think about,

00:20:12.530 --> 00:20:15.330
what do you think a common
student mistake would be?

00:20:15.330 --> 00:20:17.320 position:64%
Not what do you think the idea answer is?

00:20:17.320 --> 00:20:22.270 position:72%
But rather, what do you think a common mistake
would be if you were to give this to students?

00:20:22.270 --> 00:20:27.510 position:73%
What might they answer that might trip them up?

00:20:27.510 --> 00:20:29.690 position:59%
So think about that and then jot down,

00:20:29.690 --> 00:20:32.870 position:58%
what do you think some common student
mistakes with this task would be?

00:20:32.870 --> 00:20:35.510 position:61%
And write those in the comment section.

00:20:35.510 --> 00:21:26.920
[ Silence ]

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:33.710 position:61%
So people have really hit on the issues
of what the most common mistakes are.

00:21:33.710 --> 00:21:36.420
Without a doubt.

00:21:36.420 --> 00:21:40.180
And we piloted this task now
with thousands of students.

00:21:40.180 --> 00:21:45.910
And the types of mistakes that
you are identifying are spot on.

00:21:45.910 --> 00:21:49.230
And so I'd like to show you
a few of the responses.

00:21:49.230 --> 00:21:53.760
This response is by far the
most common one that we see.

00:21:53.760 --> 00:21:56.410
The student wrote, "True."

00:21:56.410 --> 00:21:58.150 position:63%
True as in, it would be a useful source.

00:21:58.150 --> 00:22:00.720
"Because you can see how they're
interacting with each other.

00:22:00.720 --> 00:22:04.960
Without any picture, you couldn't
really see how Wampanoag Indians

00:22:04.960 --> 00:22:07.640 position:70%
and the Puritans interacted with each other."

00:22:07.640 --> 00:22:11.890
So this student is essentially
saying, yes, it's a great source.

00:22:11.890 --> 00:22:14.030
Of course it would be useful.

00:22:14.030 --> 00:22:18.090 position:70%
If you didn't show me this picture, how could
I know anything about the First Thanksgiving?

00:22:18.090 --> 00:22:20.180 position:75%
Essentially, a picture's worth a thousand words.

00:22:20.180 --> 00:22:25.570
Which is, as several people noted
in the comments, it seems like more

00:22:25.570 --> 00:22:29.680
than anything the student is
matching the image of Thanksgiving

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:32.310 position:63%
to their own beliefs about Thanksgiving.

00:22:32.310 --> 00:22:38.160 position:70%
This matches what I think Thanksgiving looked
like, and as a result it's a useful source.

00:22:38.160 --> 00:22:43.270
The second most common type of
response looked more like this one.

00:22:43.270 --> 00:22:45.450
The student in this case disagreed.

00:22:45.450 --> 00:22:49.880
And they said that it would not
be a useful source for historians.

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:53.510 position:66%
The student wrote, "As soon as the
settlers arrived, there was mass curiosity

00:22:53.510 --> 00:22:55.600 position:59%
which turned into violence and hatred.

00:22:55.600 --> 00:22:59.460
There was never such a "party"
between the two peoples.

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:02.100 position:66%
They couldn't even understand each other."

00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:05.740
And so at first, you know, the
student said something good, right?

00:23:05.740 --> 00:23:10.740 position:61%
They're trying to bring some background
knowledge to bear on the source.

00:23:10.740 --> 00:23:15.410 position:58%
And they're trying to have a
critical examination of the document.

00:23:15.410 --> 00:23:18.630 position:56%
But there are also some errors here.

00:23:18.630 --> 00:23:21.830
You know, the students say
that there never such a party.

00:23:21.830 --> 00:23:26.440 position:67%
But we have documentary evidence that there
was a meal held between the two groups.

00:23:26.440 --> 00:23:30.600 position:66%
We can certainly argue about the nature of
the meal, but there's certainly evidence

00:23:30.600 --> 00:23:36.840 position:64%
that the two groups understood each other
and even could understand each other

00:23:36.840 --> 00:23:42.050
with Squanto having some exposure
to English and being able to speak.

00:23:42.050 --> 00:23:47.800
But regardless, the bigger
issue is that in both the cases,

00:23:47.800 --> 00:23:51.700
the students have totally
ignored the date of the document.

00:23:51.700 --> 00:23:56.900 position:63%
And have not addressed the problems that
are associated with using a document

00:23:56.900 --> 00:24:04.090 position:69%
that was created 311 years after the event,
as a source of information about that event.

00:24:04.090 --> 00:24:10.490 position:67%
And to acknowledge the problems that result
from such a gap in time between the date

00:24:10.490 --> 00:24:15.140
of production and the event
that it seeks to depict.

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:19.660 position:75%
And so as a teacher, from those quick
responses I get immediate feedback about whether

00:24:19.660 --> 00:24:24.390 position:67%
or not my students can attend to one aspect
of historical thinking, which is sourcing.

00:24:24.390 --> 00:24:27.750 position:70%
At this point, though, some people say great,

00:24:27.750 --> 00:24:35.040
why don't you just make this
into a multiple choice question?

00:24:35.040 --> 00:24:37.090
And get rid of all this writing?

00:24:37.090 --> 00:24:40.010 position:56%
It's a lot easier to score
multiple choice questions than it is

00:24:40.010 --> 00:24:43.240 position:64%
to have even short constructed responses.

00:24:43.240 --> 00:24:46.360
But what we think is that
there is an enormous amount

00:24:46.360 --> 00:24:49.480 position:73%
that we can learn from short student responses.

00:24:49.480 --> 00:24:54.430 position:67%
So for instance, this student disagreed and
said that it would not be a good source.

00:24:54.430 --> 00:24:57.330 position:63%
So if it was a multiple choice question,
this student would have gotten it right

00:24:57.330 --> 00:24:59.400
because they're saying no,
it's not a useful source.

00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:00.830
But their reasoning is interesting.

00:25:00.830 --> 00:25:03.710
The student wrote, "Painted
by a white person from Europe,

00:25:03.710 --> 00:25:08.050 position:73%
of course they will be extremely biased in
order to bring to light a highly positive image

00:25:08.050 --> 00:25:11.700
of the Europeans as to excite
more foreign expeditions.

00:25:11.700 --> 00:25:17.350
Because the Indians look
sooo friendly and thankful."

00:25:17.350 --> 00:25:23.390
So, although they might have
gotten it right in terms of arguing

00:25:23.390 --> 00:25:28.260 position:69%
that the document would not be a useful one,
their reasoning is clearly pretty suspect.

00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:33.810 position:59%
First, they assume that J.L.G. Ferris
must be white and must be from Europe.

00:25:33.810 --> 00:25:37.720
But moreover, they seem to
have ignored the date as well.

00:25:37.720 --> 00:25:43.080 position:56%
Because they seem to think that in
1932 the Europeans were still trying

00:25:43.080 --> 00:25:47.260
to excite more foreign expeditions
to the new world.

00:25:47.260 --> 00:25:49.930
Deeply problematic.

00:25:49.930 --> 00:25:53.430
But as a teacher, there's something
good going on here as well.

00:25:53.430 --> 00:25:58.170 position:69%
The student is acknowledging that the author
of a document -- the artist in this case --

00:25:58.170 --> 00:26:00.500 position:61%
influences the content of the document.

00:26:00.500 --> 00:26:01.730
That's what we want students to do.

00:26:01.730 --> 00:26:08.410 position:69%
We want them to think about the way in which
the author carefully shapes the content

00:26:08.410 --> 00:26:09.410
of a document.

00:26:09.410 --> 00:26:16.100 position:75%
So if this is my student, I can say, "I'm really
glad that you're paying attention to the way

00:26:16.100 --> 00:26:18.070 position:69%
in which the author influences the document.

00:26:18.070 --> 00:26:22.140 position:56%
But we also really need to pay
attention to the date of a document.

00:26:22.140 --> 00:26:27.510 position:61%
And that's going to be a crucial piece
of information to think about as well."

00:26:27.510 --> 00:26:30.870
We also in some cases see
really polished responses.

00:26:30.870 --> 00:26:34.110 position:58%
This student wrote -- and it was an
eighth grader, as a matter of fact --

00:26:34.110 --> 00:26:38.220 position:59%
wrote, "This painting was drawn 311
years after the actual event happened.

00:26:38.220 --> 00:26:40.580 position:67%
There's no evidence of historical accuracy,

00:26:40.580 --> 00:26:44.030
as we do not know if the artist
did research before painting this,

00:26:44.030 --> 00:26:49.590 position:67%
or if he just drew what is a
stereotypical Pilgrim and Indian painting."

00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:51.430 position:61%
Really impressive for an eighth grader.

00:26:51.430 --> 00:26:57.320 position:73%
I did not have a lot of tenth graders when I
was teaching who could formulate this response.

00:26:57.320 --> 00:27:00.330 position:75%
And the student has nicer handwriting than I do.

00:27:00.330 --> 00:27:07.510 position:70%
But what is striking is, the student has both
identified the danger of using a document

00:27:07.510 --> 00:27:10.930 position:72%
so far removed from the event that it depicts.

00:27:10.930 --> 00:27:15.280 position:70%
But they've also acknowledged that if we knew
more about what the artist did in advance

00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:20.960 position:59%
of creating the document, it might
change the way that we think about it.

00:27:20.960 --> 00:27:26.470 position:56%
The document -- this answer also
shows something that we've seen over

00:27:26.470 --> 00:27:29.890 position:56%
and over again with these responses.

00:27:29.890 --> 00:27:36.070 position:67%
Which is, there isn't a clear developmental
trajectory in terms of student thinking.

00:27:36.070 --> 00:27:38.880
In other words, it's not as
though seniors can engage,

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:43.260
only high school seniors can
engage in this type of thinking.

00:27:43.260 --> 00:27:45.710 position:69%
In fact, as this eighth grader demonstrates,

00:27:45.710 --> 00:27:48.960
many students can engage
in this type of thinking.

00:27:48.960 --> 00:27:52.870 position:72%
Perhaps not surprisingly, what we found is
it's the students who've been taught to engage

00:27:52.870 --> 00:27:54.680
in historical thinking who do it.

00:27:54.680 --> 00:27:57.250 position:75%
And it's the students who have not who struggle.

00:27:57.250 --> 00:28:03.140 position:64%
So for instance, we've given this task to
high school seniors who have gotten fives

00:28:03.140 --> 00:28:07.940 position:70%
on the AP U.S. History exam, and they've
missed the date of the Thanksgiving painting.

00:28:07.940 --> 00:28:11.780
And I don't mean that in any way
as a knock against those students.

00:28:11.780 --> 00:28:14.110 position:66%
I'm very confident that with a few minutes

00:28:14.110 --> 00:28:16.460
of instruction they would see
the importance of the date.

00:28:16.460 --> 00:28:20.690 position:58%
They just haven't been taught to look
carefully at the dates of documents.

00:28:20.690 --> 00:28:26.740 position:59%
That, especially in the past, has not
been heavily emphasized in AP testing.

00:28:26.740 --> 00:28:32.830 position:66%
In contrast, we've seen fifth graders who
have come up with really strong responses.

00:28:32.830 --> 00:28:36.470 position:69%
Not quite as polished, and the
handwriting's not quite as good as this one.

00:28:36.470 --> 00:28:39.590
But we've seen fifth graders
do it because they've been

00:28:39.590 --> 00:28:43.130 position:70%
in classrooms where this has been emphasized.

00:28:43.130 --> 00:28:47.910
However, none of these tasks are
based on only a single document.

00:28:47.910 --> 00:28:52.550
Instead, they are -- we intend
them to be flexible

00:28:52.550 --> 00:28:54.480 position:72%
so that we can make multiple versions of them.

00:28:54.480 --> 00:28:56.070
This is the exact same assessment.

00:28:56.070 --> 00:28:59.280
But instead of a Thanksgiving
painting, we have an engraving

00:28:59.280 --> 00:29:02.470 position:63%
of the signing of the Mayflower Compact.

00:29:02.470 --> 00:29:05.130
And again, there's a big
gap in time between the date

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:08.450 position:72%
of the document and the event that it depicts.

00:29:08.450 --> 00:29:11.760
And so if I'm a teacher I could
use the Thanksgiving assessment

00:29:11.760 --> 00:29:13.530 position:56%
at the beginning of the school year.

00:29:13.530 --> 00:29:17.370
And then give it back to students
and give them some feedback

00:29:17.370 --> 00:29:18.750 position:59%
about what strong responses look like.

00:29:18.750 --> 00:29:23.340 position:69%
And then I could give them another one a few
weeks later, like this one, to see whether

00:29:23.340 --> 00:29:27.060
or not they've really internalized
those ideas and they have been able

00:29:27.060 --> 00:29:35.480 position:66%
to track the crucial nature of considering
the source when evaluating documents.

00:29:35.480 --> 00:29:41.910
So when we think about HATs,
we have made them to be short,

00:29:41.910 --> 00:29:44.240
so that they can be done
quickly in five or ten minutes.

00:29:44.240 --> 00:29:47.020 position:69%
And they target specific content and skills.

00:29:47.020 --> 00:29:49.740 position:72%
So in this case it's very much about sourcing,

00:29:49.740 --> 00:29:54.720
and one aspect of sourcing,
the date of the document.

00:29:54.720 --> 00:29:59.450
So that we can get quick feedback
about students' ability with them.

00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:01.520
Similarly, it gives evidence
of student thinking.

00:30:01.520 --> 00:30:08.890 position:75%
So as teachers we get some immediate information
that we can use to shape our next steps

00:30:08.890 --> 00:30:10.810 position:61%
and it doesn't take us hours to get it.

00:30:10.810 --> 00:30:15.240 position:72%
We can quickly even flip through, even if we
don't give students detailed written feedback,

00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:17.930 position:67%
we can get a temperature for our classroom.

00:30:17.930 --> 00:30:21.450 position:69%
Which will shape our next steps as teachers.

00:30:21.450 --> 00:30:23.690 position:70%
And hopefully they're more accessible, right?

00:30:23.690 --> 00:30:26.980
That if some of our students are
not yet ready for the really great,

00:30:26.980 --> 00:30:28.900 position:70%
rich challenged of a document-based question,

00:30:28.900 --> 00:30:33.190 position:69%
that we can have them complete these shorter
tasks in the building block towards some

00:30:33.190 --> 00:30:37.420 position:67%
of those more complex types of assessments.

00:30:37.420 --> 00:30:41.340 position:59%
Often at this point after looking at
that assessment, some people will say,

00:30:41.340 --> 00:30:45.620 position:63%
so do you guys just care about skills
and you don't care about content at all?

00:30:45.620 --> 00:30:47.620 position:69%
And they couldn't be further from the truth.

00:30:47.620 --> 00:30:53.810 position:69%
When we constructed our domain of what we
were seeking to assess, historical thinking,

00:30:53.810 --> 00:30:57.850 position:67%
we place historical knowledge as one of the
three main pillars of historical thinking.

00:30:57.850 --> 00:31:03.080 position:59%
Students need to know content in order
to engage with historical documents.

00:31:03.080 --> 00:31:05.560 position:63%
And then there's evaluation of evidence.

00:31:05.560 --> 00:31:08.630
Students need to consider the
source and place it in context.

00:31:08.630 --> 00:31:11.120
And corroborate it, to consider
multiple documents,

00:31:11.120 --> 00:31:14.100
and to look for points of
similarity and difference.

00:31:14.100 --> 00:31:16.880 position:63%
In order to build a historical argument.

00:31:16.880 --> 00:31:22.140 position:67%
And so other assessments that we've created
address historical content very directly.

00:31:22.140 --> 00:31:26.030 position:69%
This is an assessment that's about students'
knowledge of the Civil Rights Movement.

00:31:26.030 --> 00:31:27.370 position:63%
And it would be an assessment you'd give

00:31:27.370 --> 00:31:30.050
after you had taught students
about the Civil Rights Movement.

00:31:30.050 --> 00:31:35.550
And it draws on two letters
from the archives of the NAACP.

00:31:35.550 --> 00:31:40.040
And the first letter, both written
to the executive director of NAACP.

00:31:40.040 --> 00:31:43.890 position:72%
The first letter says, "Before I received your
letter today, I had been in to the President.

00:31:43.890 --> 00:31:47.590
And he said the difficulty is that
it is unconstitutional, apparently,

00:31:47.590 --> 00:31:50.860
for the federal government to
step into the lynching situation.

00:31:50.860 --> 00:31:53.960 position:59%
The President feels that lynching is
a question of education in the states.

00:31:53.960 --> 00:31:57.640 position:70%
I'm deeply troubled about the whole
situation, as it seems to be a terrible thing

00:31:57.640 --> 00:32:00.320
to stand by and let it continue."

00:32:00.320 --> 00:32:06.060 position:58%
Students then read a second document,
also from the NAACP about conditions

00:32:06.060 --> 00:32:08.260
at a previously all-white school.

00:32:08.260 --> 00:32:11.460 position:69%
The letter reads, "Conditions are yet
pretty rough in the school for the children.

00:32:11.460 --> 00:32:14.270 position:70%
The treatment of the children had been
getting steadily worse for the last two weeks

00:32:14.270 --> 00:32:16.720
in the form of kicking, spitting,
and general abuse.

00:32:16.720 --> 00:32:20.650 position:67%
As a result of our visit, stronger measures
are being taken against the white students

00:32:20.650 --> 00:32:22.300 position:69%
who are guilty of committing these offenses.

00:32:22.300 --> 00:32:27.030 position:59%
The President of the United States was
very much concerned about the crisis."

00:32:27.030 --> 00:32:33.970 position:66%
And instead of asking students a question
like, what was the year of Brown v. Board?

00:32:33.970 --> 00:32:36.750
Or when did lynching reach
its peak in the United States?

00:32:36.750 --> 00:32:39.850
We asked a very basic question,
which is, which letter came first?

00:32:39.850 --> 00:32:42.480
We didn't give them the dates
of the documents in this case.

00:32:42.480 --> 00:32:47.300 position:70%
Instead we wanted them to use their knowledge
of the Civil Rights Movement in order

00:32:47.300 --> 00:32:49.730 position:56%
to place these documents in context.

00:32:49.730 --> 00:32:50.740
Which one came first?

00:32:50.740 --> 00:32:57.740 position:70%
And what from the document provided them the
necessary information to answer the question?

00:32:57.740 --> 00:33:05.580 position:73%
So if students don't know about the Civil
Rights Movement, they might answer it this way.

00:33:05.580 --> 00:33:07.850
Student wrote, "Letter B
was likely written first,

00:33:07.850 --> 00:33:10.840
because letter B is addressing
the unsegregation of schools,

00:33:10.840 --> 00:33:13.890
and letter A is about the
response to the issue -- lynching."

00:33:13.890 --> 00:33:17.330 position:59%
And there's a certain cause-and-effect
logic going on here.

00:33:17.330 --> 00:33:21.720 position:66%
But it's simply historically incorrect
that following the integration of schools,

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:26.190 position:70%
although there's some violence, there is not
widespread lynching that happens as a result.

00:33:26.190 --> 00:33:31.110 position:67%
The student does not have a grasp of the
Civil Rights Movement and the way in which,

00:33:31.110 --> 00:33:35.780 position:73%
over the course of the 20th Century, the
federal government became increasingly involved

00:33:35.780 --> 00:33:38.070 position:70%
in acting on the behalf of African-Americans.

00:33:38.070 --> 00:33:40.530 position:70%
And intervening in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:33:40.530 --> 00:33:46.720 position:70%
Moreover, that the lynching was much more a
problem in the first part of the 20th Century

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:50.480 position:63%
when it reached a sort of critical mass.

00:33:50.480 --> 00:33:53.990
In contrast, the integration
of schools happened later.

00:33:53.990 --> 00:33:56.540
And so as a teacher we can
get some quick feedback about,

00:33:56.540 --> 00:34:00.040 position:61%
do my students have the broad
narrative of the Civil Rights Movement?

00:34:00.040 --> 00:34:03.520 position:58%
Do they understand the broad
contours of the Movement rather than,

00:34:03.520 --> 00:34:07.760 position:67%
do they know about specific names or dates?

00:34:07.760 --> 00:34:10.130
Although those are important,
this is a different type of task

00:34:10.130 --> 00:34:13.950 position:58%
