00:35:50.300 --> 00:35:54.520
&gt;&gt; Imagine if real-life decisions
were like a multiple choice exam.

00:35:54.520 --> 00:35:59.960 position:61%
&gt;&gt; First question, "To surprise the
British troops in Trenton, should I A),

00:35:59.960 --> 00:36:04.480 position:58%
dress my troops up as a marching band
and offer to play a free concert?

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:10.100 position:69%
B), Hide my troops in a giant horse and
present it as a victory gift to the British?

00:36:10.100 --> 00:36:13.890 position:75%
C), Cross the icy Delaware in a rickety rowboat?

00:36:13.890 --> 00:36:18.740 position:70%
D) Stay in my tent because it's cold
outside, and let someone else deal with them?

00:36:18.740 --> 00:36:21.810
&gt;&gt; Seems ridiculous, right?

00:36:21.810 --> 00:36:24.340
Essentially, that's what
multiple choice tests do.

00:36:24.340 --> 00:36:28.590 position:58%
They penalize kids for not knowing
facts that are ripped out of context.

00:36:28.590 --> 00:36:32.500 position:67%
On the opposite end of the spectrum are
document-based questions requiring students

00:36:32.500 --> 00:36:36.230 position:56%
to analyze and write a college-level
essay based on ten documents.

00:36:36.230 --> 00:36:41.360 position:64%
But what if your students haven't learned
to analyze one document, let alone ten?

00:36:41.360 --> 00:36:44.040 position:72%
As an educator, do you have any other options?

00:36:44.040 --> 00:36:45.970
Now you do.

00:36:45.970 --> 00:36:50.530 position:58%
Beyond the Bubble was developed by
the Stanford History Education Group.

00:36:50.530 --> 00:36:53.930
And unlocks the vast digital
archive of the Library of Congress

00:36:53.930 --> 00:37:05.220
to create a new generation
of history assessments.

00:37:05.220 --> 00:37:23.350
Our easy to use assessments capture
students' knowledge in action.

00:37:23.350 --> 00:37:30.970 position:73%
Rather than their recall of disconnected facts.

00:37:30.970 --> 00:37:34.150
We call our exercises History
Assessments of Thinking, or HATs.

00:37:34.150 --> 00:37:35.620
HATs ask students to engage
in historical reasoning

00:37:35.620 --> 00:37:36.790 position:67%
as they critically examine primary sources.

00:37:36.790 --> 00:37:38.080 position:72%
Most HATs take just a few minutes to complete.

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:38.680
And they're easy to score.

00:37:38.680 --> 00:37:41.230 position:75%
They also come with interactive scoring rubrics,
samples of student work, and Going Deeper videos

00:37:41.230 --> 00:37:42.580
that extend your understanding
of these assessments.

00:37:42.580 --> 00:37:44.470 position:59%
Your students' short written responses
to these HATs will give you access

00:37:44.470 --> 00:37:45.220
to what they are really thinking.

00:37:45.220 --> 00:37:46.180 position:66%
