00:46:02.570 --> 00:46:11.410 position:59%
So how can you address the errors when
looking at the students' thinking?

00:46:11.410 --> 00:46:13.340
&gt;&gt; Really, really good questions.

00:46:13.340 --> 00:46:19.560 position:75%
You know, and I think our hope is that these
types of tasks provide opportunities to surface.

00:46:19.560 --> 00:46:22.910
What are some of the misconceptions
or errors in student thinking?

00:46:22.910 --> 00:46:25.720 position:70%
So that we can address them as a whole class.

00:46:25.720 --> 00:46:29.630 position:59%
You know, we work with a teacher in
San Francisco Unified School District.

00:46:29.630 --> 00:46:32.730
And she gave the Thanksgiving
task on the first day of school.

00:46:32.730 --> 00:46:35.540
Because she knows that almost none
of her students will get it right.

00:46:35.540 --> 00:46:38.890
She doesn't even grade the task;
she just has everybody do it.

00:46:38.890 --> 00:46:42.800 position:63%
And she knows that probably 90% of the
students will say it's a great resource.

00:46:42.800 --> 00:46:46.810 position:66%
And then instead of even spending the time
to mark up all of them, she goes over,

00:46:46.810 --> 00:46:48.730 position:63%
"What does a strong response look like?"

00:46:48.730 --> 00:46:52.970
So that it's an opportunity to
build student understanding of,

00:46:52.970 --> 00:46:54.590 position:66%
it's really important to look at the date.

00:46:54.590 --> 00:46:58.400 position:58%
And in this class we're going to
care about where documents came from.

00:46:58.400 --> 00:46:59.830
And so I think that's one way.

00:46:59.830 --> 00:47:05.130 position:66%
And then the other is, you know, of the
idea of formative assessment is to be able

00:47:05.130 --> 00:47:07.470
to provide students with a goal
of what we're trying to do.

00:47:07.470 --> 00:47:10.310
Ultimately this is what we
want to be able to do in terms

00:47:10.310 --> 00:47:12.210 position:70%
of our thinking, we want to source documents.

00:47:12.210 --> 00:47:15.170
And that the tasks are a way
for us to identify the gap

00:47:15.170 --> 00:47:18.650 position:69%
between where we ultimately want our
students to be and where they currently are.

00:47:18.650 --> 00:47:22.020
And it's a way for students to
see where they currently are,

00:47:22.020 --> 00:47:24.100 position:67%
and have a sense of where they can go next.

00:47:24.100 --> 00:47:27.330 position:63%
And so I think there are ways in which
we can do some with individual feedback.

00:47:27.330 --> 00:47:30.840 position:64%
But also given, you know, the constraints
of if you have 150 kids in your classes,

00:47:30.840 --> 00:47:35.500 position:64%
you can't write even short responses on
all of these types of tasks all the time.

00:47:35.500 --> 00:47:39.620 position:72%
So figuring out other ways to provide
constructive, meaningful feedback that's based

00:47:39.620 --> 00:47:42.490 position:72%
on sort of the overall place your class is in.

00:47:42.490 --> 00:47:45.900 position:63%
And then if there are a few students who
are, you know, way above or way below,

00:47:45.900 --> 00:47:48.280 position:58%
that you can work with them
individually but have tried to figure

00:47:48.280 --> 00:47:52.990
out how we can help move the
whole class forward in general.

